After a first look at the dataset and its feature, we can split the variables in two main groups:

  • Demographic: these are related to the donor and their demographics. DONOR_AGE, DONOR_GENDER, INCOME_GROUP, MEDIAN_HOUSEHOLD_INCOME, URBANICITY are some examples of features that pertain to the donor and their social and economic reality.
  • Donation: these are related to the donor's donation history and other charity functional features: PEP_STAR, IN_HOUSE, PUBLISHED_PHONE, FREQUENCY_STATUS_97NK are some examples of this type.

Only a small part of the individuals donated. As we will see further ahead in the project, this will imply some restrictions when choosing which performance metrics to measure.

Based on the data distrubtion, we have taken considered the following cut offs to define a new feature named DONATION_TYPE, whose values describe ranges of the donation amount (DA) reported in feature TARGET_D when it takes up a value different that zero, that is, when an individual is a donor:

  • A - DA >= 50
  • B - 20 <= DA < 50
  • C - 13 <= DA < 20
  • D - 10 <= DA < 13
  • E - DA < 10
In [191]:
# creating a list for our classes according to the different threshold donations
thresholds = [
    (donors['TARGET_D']  >= 50),
    (donors['TARGET_D'] < 50) & (donors['TARGET_D']  >= 20),
    (donors['TARGET_D'] < 20) & (donors['TARGET_D']  >= 13),
    (donors['TARGET_D'] < 13) & (donors['TARGET_D']  >= 10),
    (donors['TARGET_D'] < 10)
    ]

# creating a list of the classes
values = ['A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E']

# creating a new column, representing an ordinal feature
#using np.select to assign values to DONATION_TYPE using the above lists as arguments
donors['DONATION_TYPE'] = np.select(thresholds, values, default=np.nan)

2.4. Missing Values¶

In [18]:
na_found=donors.isna().sum().any()
if na_found==True:
    total_na = donors.isnull().sum()
    percent_na = round(donors.isnull().sum()/donors.isnull().count()*100,5)
    donors_df2 = pd.concat([percent_na, total_na], axis=1, keys=["% of NA", "Total NA"])
    dtypes = []
    for i in donors.columns:
        dtype = str(donors[i].dtype)
        dtypes.append(dtype)
    donors_df2['Type'] = dtypes
    donors_df2 = donors_df2.sort_values('% of NA', ascending=False)

Seven features were found to have missing values. It is important to highlight that the target variable TARGET_D has a considerable number of NAs, totalling 75% of the observations - as confirmed previously, this is due to the fact that 75% of individuals have not donated, hence their amount of donation does not exist.

Additionally, WEALTH_RATING, INCOME_GROUP, SES, DONOR_AGE and URBANICITY all have a high number of NA values, with the first three being the most problematic as the percentage of missing entries is above 20 %.

For these features we will have to find different imputation methods.

One way to treat these missing values would be to impute the mode to all missing values of these two features. However, as the number of missing values is too high, this would severely impact the dataset and greatly skew the observations towards the most frequent class. In this case, the mode would refer to classes 5 and 9, for INCOME_GROUP and WEALTH_RATING respectively.

We also can't just remove the rows with NA values because that would cut almost half of the dataset. A possible solution would be to evaluate if these two features are needed, as there could be features that show the same type of information as these two. In this case, we are looking for features that convey economic information about the donors.

Looking at the dataset, there are other features that represent economic data: PER_CAPITA_INCOME, MEDIAN_HOUSEHOLD_INCOME and SES. It can be interesting to look at the correlation between WEALTH_RATING and INCOME_GROUP and these features.

2.5. Dropping Features¶

Looking at the features' descriptions, we can immediately point out some that are meaningless for the problem at hand and, hence, will be dropped:

  • CONTROL_NUMBER: this is a unique identifier for each donor, it has no impact in the donation.
  • OVERLAY_SOURCE: we will assume that the data source is not relevant for the prediction.
  • FILE_AVG_GIFT: this feature is identical to LIFETIME_AVG_GIFT_AMT, according to the dataset info.
  • PEP_STAR: which takes up value 1 if the donor has a STAR status and 0 otherwise will be removed as this information is already displayed in the feature 'RECENCY_STATUS_96NK' by the class S and by the remaining ones, respectively.
  • RECENT_STAR_STATUS: which takes up value 1 if the donor has reached STAR status 4 years ago and 0 otherwise will be removed as this information is already displayed in the feature 'RECENCY_STATUS_96NK' by the class S and by the remaining ones, respectively.
  • CLUSTER_CODE: There are 54 unique values for this variable. Given that this feature reflects socioeconomic status, urbanicity, ethnicity, and other demographic characteristics, we consider that such information is already reflected in other features of this dataset so we will drop it.
  • NUMBER_PROM_12: the data illustrated in this feature is already represented by the feature 'CARD_PROM_12'
  • PCT_ATTRIBUTE3 and PCT_ATTRIBUTE4: these features show the % of veterans of WWII and Vietnam in the neighborhood where the donor lives. However, the % of all veterans is already in PCT_ATTRIBUTE2. This means these features are redundant and should be dropped. Also, we should rename PCT_ATTRIBUTE1 and 2 to something more clear: 1 to PCT_MILITARY and 2 to PCT_VETERANS

Categorical Attributes¶

In [73]:
def plot_categorical(var, data=donors):
    """
    Creates a count plot, a bar plot for DONATION_TYPE, the mean for TARGET_D and a boxplot for TARGET_D for a 
    categorical variable of the donors dataset. 
    Requires: var is a string, the name of a column of the donors dataset.
    """
    # countplot
    sns.countplot(x=var, data = data)
    plt.show()
    
    # barplot
    cross_table = pd.crosstab(index=data[var], columns=data["DONATION_TYPE"])
    cross_table.plot(kind="bar", figsize=(6,6))
    plt.show()
    
    # boxplot
    sns.boxplot(x=var, y='TARGET_D', data=data)
    plt.show()
    
    # mean
    mean = data["TARGET_D"].groupby(data[var]).mean().sort_values(ascending=False)
    print(mean)

Task 1.1) Predicting Donation (binary classification task) - TARGET_B¶

We had already previously observed the feature TARGET_B, we were dealing with an imbalanced data set. When learning from data sets that contain very few instances of the minority class, in many cases the algorithm tends to favor the majority class while the minority class usually represents the most important concept to be learned (individuals who donated).

def perf_metrics(grid_search_model, y_pred_model, X_test, y_test):
    print(grid_search_model.estimator, "Results: ")
    confusion_matrix_test = confusion_matrix(y_pred_model, y_test) 
    print("Confusion Matrix Test Set")
    TP = confusion_matrix_test[1, 1]
    TN = confusion_matrix_test[0, 0]
    FP = confusion_matrix_test[0, 1]
    FN = confusion_matrix_test[1, 0]
    print(confusion_matrix_test)
    print("In the test set:")
    print(TN,"individuals were correctly classified as 'not-donors' (TN).")
    print(TP,"individuals were correctly classified as 'donors' (TP).")
    print(FP,"individuals were wrongly classified as 'donors' (FP).")
    print(FN,"individuals were wrongly classified as 'not-donors' (FN).")
    accuracy_test = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_model)
    print("The model predicted {}% of the individuals correctly in the test set.".format(np.round(accuracy_test*100,2)))
    precision_test = precision_score(y_test, y_pred_model)
    print("The model predicted correctly that an individual will donate {}% of the times in the test set.".format(np.round(precision_test*100,4)))
    recall_test = recall_score(y_test,y_pred_model)
    print("The model predicted the donation of {}% of the passengers who actually donated in the test set.".format(np.round(recall_test*100,4)))
    f1_test = f1_score(y_test,y_pred_model) #F1 score can be interpreted as a weighted average of the precision and recall
    #best value F1=1, worst value F1=0
    print("The F1 score is",round(f1_test,4))
    
    print ("Area under the ROC = ", np.round(roc_auc_score(y_test, grid_search_model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]),2))
    
    y_predict_proba = grid_search_model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
    fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_predict_proba)
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
    roc_auc_score(y_test, y_predict_proba) #AUC will remain the same regardless of varying threshold

    plt.figure()
    lw = 2
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange',
             lw=lw, label='ROC curve (area = %0.2f)' % roc_auc)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=lw, linestyle='--')
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.show()

    print ("Best Parameters", grid_search_model.best_params_)
    print ("Best Estimator",grid_search_model.best_estimator_)

The 'positive class'/'1' in our model happens when an individual donated, so ideally we want to optimize it for sensitivity (TPR). This is due to the fact that False Positives (donors who are predicted as 'non-donors') are more acceptable than False Negatives ('non-donors' who are predicted as to have 'donors').

However if we want to increase the recall/sensitivy of our model, this may result in a decrease of the precision (depending on the threshold).

Task 1.2) Predicting Donation TYPE (multiclass classification) - DONATION_TYPE¶

We will now proceed with the classification of a multiclass feature, the "DONATION_TYPE" feature.

This feature was not part of the original dataset, but instead it was created as a way to divide and classify the results according to certain limitings parameters.

The Plan/Procedure to be implemented:¶

So for this seccion, the multclass classification, the plan will be the following:

Step_1: Since the "DONATION_TYPE" has a categorical output (ordinal data in this case), we will first perform a data     encoding procedure.

Step_2: We will examine the "Shape" of the "DONATION_TYPE" data and we will realize that it is unbalanced and as a consecuence we will apply the SMOTE techinique to minimize the problem. 

Step_3: A set of 5 classifiers types will be chosen and apply to perform classification. This task will include, for each classifiers, the use of the SMOTE and cross-validation techiniques.

Step_4: At the end of this task, we will compare the overall results and we will summarize the conclusion results.

1.2.1) Preprocessing Data for Multiclass Classification¶

We will now do the classification of multiclass feature target "DONATION_TYPE".

We beging this task by enconding the necessary features in order to be able to run the classification models. Then we will run one algorithm to build our classifier. This will be done five times and we will use a diferent algorithm for each type of classifier.

Cross validation will be used for each result in order to enhance our models.

1.2.2) Dealing with an unbalanced data problem¶

As we previuslly mentioned, we are facing a problem on this dataset. The problem is that unbalanaced distribution of its values. So as a way to solve the problem and prevent this to distorce the results of each of the classifiers, we will try to "equalize" the "target" to be classfied (ie: the "DONATION_TYPE").

To do so, we are goig to use the SMOTE Technique.

The following code will give us a preview/comparion of the result of applying the SMOTE. We will print the before/after results after applying the SMOTE techinque:

fpr = dict()
tpr = dict()
roc_auc = dict()
for i in range(n_classes):
    fpr[i], tpr[i], _ = roc_curve(y_test[:, i], y_score[:, i])
    roc_auc[i] = auc(fpr[i], tpr[i])

# First aggregate all false positive rates
all_fpr = np.unique(np.concatenate([fpr[i] for i in range(n_classes)]))

# Then interpolate all ROC curves at this points
mean_tpr = np.zeros_like(all_fpr)
for i in range(n_classes):
    mean_tpr += interp(all_fpr, fpr[i], tpr[i])

# Finally average it and compute AUC
mean_tpr /= n_classes

fpr["macro"] = all_fpr
tpr["macro"] = mean_tpr
roc_auc["macro"] = auc(fpr["macro"], tpr["macro"])

# Plot all ROC curves
colors = cycle(['aqua', 'darkorange', 'cornflowerblue'])
for i, color in zip(range(n_classes), colors):
    plt.plot(fpr[i], tpr[i], color=color, lw=lw,
             label='ROC curve of class {0} (area = {1:0.2f})'
             ''.format(i, roc_auc[i]))

plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--', lw=lw)
plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('ROC for the different classes using SVM')
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.show()

Task 2 (Unsupervised Learning) - Characterizing Donors and Donation Type¶

In this task you should use unsupervised learning algorithms and try to characterize donors (people who really did a donation) and their donation type. You can use:

  • Association rule mining to find associations between the features and the target Donation/DonationTYPE.
  • Clustering algorithms to find similar groups of donors. Is it possible to find groups of donors with the same/similar DonationTYPE?
  • Be creative and define your own unsupervised analysis! What would it be interesting to find out ?

Converting every value to string¶

There are currently non-string values in the values list. We also should translate 'numerical' strings to labels that can be understood without looking at the dataframe.

In [119]:
def numVars(df):
    '''
    Returns a list of all the numerical features of a dataframe - df.
    '''
    numVars = []
    for col in df.columns:
        if df[col].dtype.name != "category":
            numVars.append(col)
    return numVars
In [120]:
def catVars(df):
    '''
    Returns a list of all the categorical features of a dataframe - df.
    '''
    catVars = []
    for col in df.columns:
        if df[col].dtype.name == "category":
            catVars.append(col)
    return catVars

All donations types have, in general, similar associations:

  • Never having donated to the in-house program is the top association in all of them;
  • Not donating to other charities and not having their number published are also associated to all donation types;
  • Active is associated to all but donation type E.
  • Being a homeowner and female are associated to all but the top donation amount.

However, there are some differences that are interesting:

  • Donation type A, the highest donation amount, is the only type associated with unknown sex. This might happen because the highest donors usually donate anonymously;
  • The 2 top donation types, A and B, are associated with 1 donation in the time period considered, depending on the donor's status. This seems to indicate that people usually donate large amounts very rarely, instead of small amounts many times.
  • The 2 lowest donation types, D and E, are associated with SES group 2. This is the only economical feature that is linked to any donation type and it is a good predictor of donation amounts for donors who belong to this group.
  • Finally, the most surprising association is that star donors are only linked to the lowest donation type - E. We have seen this before, where star donors seem to donate lower amounts than other types of donors, and hypothesized that, once donors achieve star status, they stop giving as much. This is another evidence to back that hypothesis.

3. Final Comments, Limitations and Conclusions¶

Regarding Task 1.1) Binary Classification:

The dataset we were dealing with contained very few instances of the minority class (TARGET_B = 1) which represents the most important concept to be learned (that is, an individual is predicted to be a donor). For both multiclass and binary classification problems, various data engineering techniques are practiced to handle the imbalanced data.Due to time contraints and the fact that it could have been considered to be out of the scope of the class, we have chosen not to conduct any tecnique for the binary classification task, however for the multiclassification problem we thought it would be interesting to apply SMOTE and analyse the results yielded.

For each model, we conducted a GridSearchCV with K-Fold = 10, got the best parameters and analysed the confusion matrix and the respective performance metrics.

Here an important note would to mention that when it comes the the performance metrics, for imbalanced datasets, accuracy is not an appropriate measure as it may give an outstanding performance level by classifying all the instances as the majority class, having a higher predictive accuracy over the majority class, but poorer predictive accuracy over the minority class.

As such, we have chosen Receiver Operating Characteristics (ROC) as an evaluation framework to compare across models in this Task 1.1) as well as Task 1.2). Additionally, metrics such as precision, recall and F-value have been used to understand the performance of the learning algorithm on the minority class.

The larger the value of area under the curve, the better the model performance is. The model that performed best was Logistic Regression (ROC = 0.6). A limitation interesting to further study would be related to the fact that the recall is very low on this model (due to the presence of class imbalances).

Regarding Task 1.2) Multiclass Classification:

As previously mentioned, SMOTE (synthetic minority oversampling technique) was applied as it is one of the most commonly used oversampling methods to solve the imbalance problems.

In addition to the structure for the Task 1.1), we have additionally compared the models' performance (AUROC) on both an unbalanced dataset and a balanced dataset using SMOTE.

We can conclude that the SVM model was the one which performed best, with a ROC = 0.7 using SMOTE and ROC = 0.74 on an unbalanced dataset.

Regarding Task 1.3)

After selecting the classifier which yielded the highest AUROC, we have used it to predict the feature TARGET_B on the different SES. We found that the best perfoming model was the Naive Bayes using the parameter var_smoothing (Portion of the largest variance of all features that is added to variances for calculation stability, according to the sklearn online documentation) is set equal to 0.6 for the SES = 1 (ROC = 0.59).

Regarding Task 2) Unsupervised Learning

Association Rule

As we saw before, we found some associations for TARGET_B. We concluded that a person is more likely to donate if:

  • they NEVER donated to the charity's in-house program.
  • they are female.
  • they never responded to another charity's mail.
  • they were active donors two years ago.
  • they are homeowners.
  • they do NOT have their phone published.
  • they belong to SES group 2, the second highest group.

For donation types, they follow the same general associations as TARGET_B but there are some interesting differences:

  • The highest donation amount, A, is associated with unknown sex;
  • The lowest donation amount, E, is linked to star status;
  • The 2 top donations types are associated with single yearly donations(or multi-yearly, depending on donor status).

The results we obtained are heavily dependant on the features chosen and on the type of preprocessing done to the data. If we included other categorical features that were excluded in preprocessing or if we categorized some numerical features in the dataset we could have found other associations with TARGET_B and maybe some for some DONATION_TYPE. That said, we found a decent amount of associations that create a decent target profile that can help the organization direct its solicitations to the most likely donors.

Clustering

While we looked in both methods for the cluster with the highest average donation amount, we got different profiles with k-means and hierarchical clustering.

For k-means, the best donors live in suburban environments, don't have their number published, never contributed to other charities, never donated to the charity's in-house program, are homeowners and live in neighborhoods with a high percentage of veterans.

With this method we could not associate any cluster to a particular donation type as all of the cluster follow the same general distribution of donation types.

For hierarchical, the best donors are also homeowners that live in neighborhoods with a high percentage of veterans and also never donated to the charity's in-house program. We can also conclude that they are male, active donors with high median home value but average to low median household income.

Contrary to k-means, hierarchical also allowed us to define profiles for donation types E and D. As these are the lowest donation types, this can also help the charity direct their efforts towards other types of donor profiles.

Comparing the two methods, we can see that hierarchical created clusters with more differentiated average TARGET_D amounts, helping paint a clearer picture of the highest donors. This is probably due to the characteristics of our dataset, which contains a lot of features with some kind of hierarchical order.

Similar to rule association, the results we obtained are highly dependant on the data preprocessing and on the features that were included in the clustering methods. We could've experimented using only categorical variables in the clustering and/or do a PCA of the numerical features but, once again, we feel like the results already paint a clear picture of the ideal donor profile for this charity.

Final Remarks

Overall, we think our work was positive. We understood the importance of data cleaning and preprocessing. We managed to obtain interesting and non-obvious insights from the dataset given. Additionally, we dealt with the problem of an imbalanced dataset for both classification tasks: binary and multiclass. Even though the model performances were not excellent, we got to put into practice what we had learnt about CV, best parameters and analysing a confusion matrix.

This was definitely a very interesting project in which we learned a lot and that helped us understand better the type of work that might be required of us in the future.
